After calling `soap_destroy()` you will need to call `soap_end()` to remove deserialized POD structures from gsoap-managed memory. The `soap_destroy()` call only removes C++ objects allocated in managed memory:

~~~
    soap_destroy(soap_ptr);
    soap_end(soap_ptr);
    soap_destroy(response.soap);
    soap_end(response.soap);
~~~

The above is C-style function calling. Alternatively, in C++ use the `destroy()` method that calls both `soap_destroy()` and `soap_end()` on the engine context:

~~~
    soap_ptr-&gt;destroy();
    response.soap-&gt;destroy();
~~~

Finally, I should point out that `soap_ptr` and `response.soap` are the same, because the `response.soap` engine context pointer is set to `proxy.soap`, because this is the proxy that deserialized the data. So you can just invoke `proxy.destroy()` to release managed memory:

~~~
    proxy.destroy();
~~~

If you need to retain any data before you destroy it, then use the soapcpp2-generated deep copy functions and methods using soapcpp2 option `-Ecd`. For more info, see:

- https://www.genivia.com/doc/guide/html/index.html#deep
- https://www.genivia.com/doc/databinding/html/index.html#memory2

