answers.body_markdown:
You could do this:

    if {$a in $b} {
        puts present
    } else {
        puts absent
    }

`in` is described in the [`expr` man page](https://tcl.tk/man/tcl8.6/TclCmd/expr.htm).

Or with regexp, this:


    if {[regexp -- &quot;\\m[regsub -all {\W} $a {\\&amp;}]\\M&quot; [join $b]]} {
        puts present
    } else {
        puts absent
    }

All that complication is to ensure you don&#39;t match &quot;123-txt&quot; or &quot;0123.txt&quot; or &quot;123.txt2&quot;

Tcl&#39;s `regexp` let&#39;s you provide a special prefix in a regular expression to say that the rest of the RE is a literal string. That makes doing this easy (providing you don&#39;t want anchoring):

    if {[regexp ***=$a $b]} {
        puts &quot;found!&quot;
    }

The `***=` prefix, if present, must be the first four characters of the RE.

