See, the thing is I recommend you to use python or R only for AI or ML projects,&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
1. Easy writing code in them - an AI application for which you write code in python and Java you will find that Python or R is more suitable specifically for AI applications.&lt;br&gt;
2. Libraries and frameworks - In Python and R you have extensive libraries to make your work easy- numpy, scikit-learn, keeas, tensor flow, seaborn, matplotlib and many more. If you&#39;re a beginner start with scikit-learn docs and you can create an AI in just 5 lines of code. Best for beginners.&lt;br&gt;
3. Creating visualization - Neural networks are one of the most famous AI algorithms but lot of industries prefer logistic, linear, random forest because the explainibilty of a NN is low, black box. With Python you have matplotlib and seaborn (most common which I have used) it is pretty easy to create graphs, plots and animation. Tensor board also does a good visualization.&lt;br&gt;
4. Jupyter or R studio - This is undoubtedly one of the most important feature, let&#39;s say I have a 3.5 GB word2vec model. I write a code in say, JS or Java I wait for 15 minutes for the model to load and it gives me an error that I forgot a bracket or, semicolon in Java. I fix this and now have to wait 15 minutes again. Jupyter or R studio fixes this.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
Resources-&lt;br&gt;
1. Andrew NG 3 AI and ML courses&lt;br&gt;
2. O Reilly book on practical ML &lt;br&gt;
3. Google&#39;s MLCC&lt;br&gt;
4. Tensor flow and scikit-learn docs&lt;br&gt;
And finally&lt;br&gt;
5. Stanford&#39;s course on Statistical Learning ( using R)

